Did you recruit talent for the company?
That way, you can make sure your competitors don't" steal " you.
The economy is still in a labor market that is largely dominated by workers, and this is often true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the talent •
Here are some tips to help you keep it in the workplace
.
Despite the increase recorded in the past month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be among the lowest in the world, and in the top 10 of the OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150.6 thousand unemployed, according to the CBS).
In other words, the economy is still in a labor market that is largely dominated by workers, and this is often true when it comes to the most desirable workers-the talent.
When it comes to those professionals and managers who are centers of proven knowledge, experience and ability – the trends in the labor market show that competition for them, the talent as they are called by employers, is still in full force.
What this means for employers is that in the current labor market situation they do not have the luxury of resting on their laurels even a minute after recruiting a coveted talent, for as soon as he enters the company gates, another company will try to snatch him up.
In other words, the competition for talent is so intense that even after they are recruited, they will continue to receive a variety of tempting job offers, with 30% of workers leaving within a month of starting a job.
That is why intelligent employers will immediately move from the recruitment phase of talent to the retention phase, where the path begins first and foremost by preparing in advance and taking creativity in its absorption process.
An efficient, structured and thoughtful absorption process will make talent excited about their new workplace from day one and even look forward to the future.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage a proper absorption process that will help preserve the new talent:
It's no secret - sharing and organization readiness |
Share the factors that will work with him on his recruitment, explain to them why he is vital and important to society and the role, and how you view his contribution.
A new employee who comes to a place where he is expected and understands his value will feel welcome and strive to prove the expectations that a son has.
Knowledge is power-Coordinating expectations |
On the first day, they had a meeting with the talent to coordinate expectations.
Know his professional background and see where he sees himself in the future, so you can present him with the diverse and unique tools that you and the workplace can provide him to get there.
We are all people-we know each other personally |
During the absorption days, try to get to know the talent beyond his professional qualities and take an interest in his hobbies and interests.
A new employee who takes an interest in him and allows him to exercise and express himself beyond the limits of his role will appreciate this and want to maintain it.
Curiosity advances |
Already at the absorption stage you can create attractiveness that will make the talent want to integrate quickly.
Do this not necessarily by discussing bonuses and benefits, but by exposing it to an exciting field or interesting technology, since such stimuli for creativity lead to increased curiosity and interest in the workplace.
They also encouraged the talent to voice their thoughts and opinions to the various projects within the company and made it clear to them that they were important to the organization.
The writer is CEO of Manpower Israel – the largest manpower placement company in Israel
Electrification in your Pocket: The cost of not closing the coal plants in June-NIS billion
Report by the Knesset Research and Information Center: Failure to close the Coal Plants on a date set in June 2022 is estimated at NIS 1 billion
IEC: "The policy on the use of fuels is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy"
.
The economic cost of not closing the coal plants by the June 2022 deadline is estimated at NIS 1 billion for 2022, according to a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center.
According to the report, this cost is embodied in the consumer electricity tariff, which is expected to rise in the coming months because of the dearth of coal.
In addition, in 2023, an additional surplus of coal use of approximately 900,000 tons is expected, so this will result in an additional cost to the electricity sector for not closing the coal plants, assuming that the price of natural gas will remain significantly lower relative to the price of coal.
The report said that the reduction of about one billion shekels in the electricity tariff in 2022 meant a reduction of about 4% in the electricity consumption rate for the household consumer.
In other words, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about NIS 1 billion, and the total discount that could have been for the home consumer is about 4%.
It should be noted that as part of the reform of the electricity sector, it was decided, inter alia, to establish a subsidiary of the IEC, which will establish units powered by natural gas, designed to replace the 4-1 coal units at the Orot Rabin site.
Following this decision, a government decision was made in July 2018, stating that the 4-1 coal production units at the Orot Rabin power plant should be discontinued.
The decision set timetables, so that the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, and accordingly the coal production units 4-1 will cease operating at that time.
The IEC said in response: "The policy on the use of fuels is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy.
According to the ministry's decisions, for several years a policy of reducing the use of coal to the minimum possible has been implemented in Israel even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas."
Paying the Price: Everything you need to know about Rising Interest Rates
Next week, the interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percentage point.  •
How much will the mortgage payment cost?
And what is best to do? •
All the answers
The worsening inflation rate in Israel, which has already reached more than 4% in the past year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise interest rates on the shekel as early as next week.
Analysts ' estimates range from 0.25 percent to 0.5 percent.
If interest rates did rise by half a percentage point, it would already stand at 1.25 per cent, the highest level in nine years.
For years, interest rates in the economy have been close to zero.
The sharp rise in interest rates is making mortgage repayments more expensive and putting a drastic strain on households.
With the help of Shai Tzaruz, a mortgage expert, we looked at how much we would pay more and what we should do now.
If the interest rate increases by half a percentage point , how much will the monthly payment on the mortgage cost?
On a mortgage in the amount of NIS 1.2 million, which consists of a 40% prime interest rate track, the monthly repayment will increase by NIS 125.
How much has the average mortgage increased since the beginning of the year?
Since the beginning of the year, this has been a significantly sharper increase.
This is because interest rates in the other tracks that make up a mortgage (and not just in the prime track) have also risen - in the index-linked track and in the fixed-rate track.
If the interest rate does increase by half a percentage point, the cost will amount, according to Tzaruz's estimate, to NIS 620 on a mortgage of NIS 1.2 million.
The prime track (40% in this track) will complete a cost of about NIS 280, assuming there will be an increase of another 0.5% next month.
The variable interest rate track (26.7% in this track) will complete a consideration of approximately NIS 120.
The course of fixed interest - not index-linked (33.3% in this track) will be priced at NIS 220.
So what is best to do today?
For those with a mortgage that is mostly index-linked, Bundle recommends considering recycling into non-index-linked tracks.
For mortgage-takers whose monthly repayments have increased significantly and it is difficult for them to meet the repayments, he recommends looking at refinancing a mortgage and redeploying it for a longer period.
This is to reduce payments despite the rise in interest rates, as it is always better to meet repayments rather than be insolvent.
Regarding new mortgage takers - he strongly recommends getting to know the different routes and adapting the mortgage to their financial abilities.
In the future, when interest rates fall, they will be able to refinance a mortgage with minimum early repayment fees.
With regard to apartment buyers from a contractor - a bundle recommends that you advance payments to the contractor and take out a mortgage now.
It should be taken into account that the" Building inputs index " increases the price of the property significantly even after the purchase contract is signed.
The Residential Construction Inputs Price Index has risen 6.6 per cent in the past year.
Against the background of the increase in this measure, the Banking Supervision Department announced yesterday that it was considering requiring the creation of a mechanism that would allow the clustering to be included in the mortgages, but the final decision on the matter has not yet been made.
