In addition, from August 10, an additional reduction of another half shekel will be determined, so that only from this date will the price of a liter of gasoline be reduced by one shekel until November 15, 2022.
This is reported by the Tax Authority.
"We have reached a point where I can't remember five months in a row of excess state revenues.
We started a few months ago with the issue of reducing the tax on diesel.
We've been working for a week on a four - month extension of the excise, petrol and diesel tax-instead of half a shekel.
It's good for the industry and the citizen.
If we cut it, it would affect inflation, reduce production and ease the cost of living.
As finance minister, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus first of all on this," Lieberman told the Israel Democracy Institute's Horowitz Conference on Economics and Society.
At present, more than half of the price of fuel is the taxes collected by the government (excise tax and VAT) - and this is a high tax rate compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic effect on the cost of living in the economy - because it affects both household and business expenses, public transport and air travel prices, transportation costs and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the friendliest city for business
Petah Tikva came in second place in the Economy Ministry's ranking of doing business •
Next: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon Lezion •
Minister Barbie: "The Corona has stressed the importance of local government in business development"
.
Ashdod is the most friendly city for small and medium-sized businesses.
This is the third year in a row, according to the Small and Medium - Sized Business Index of the Ministry of Economy and Industry, which ranked local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva and in third place Rehovot.
They are followed in order: Ashkelon, Rishon Lezion, Tel Aviv־Jaffa, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Be'er Sheva, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya and Bnei Brak.
The agency compiles the Local Authority index.
This is the fifth time and aims to serve as a tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance to other authorities in a variety of parameters, as well as analyze its performance in the areas in which it is active.
The index is based on several parameters examined by each authority, which examine the level of"friendliness" of the authority to businesses in its field.
The measure divides the authorities into three groups of size according to the number of residents, since a local authority of up to 50,000 residents is not comparable to a local authority of more than 150,000 residents.
Tel Aviv surged this year
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different ratings for each local authority: satisfaction of businesses, accessibility to tenders, accessibility of information and Arnona.
The ranking shows that Ramat Gan dropped from second place to eighth place, Bat Yam dropped from fourth place to 12th place and Netanya dropped from fifth place to 13th place.
A decline in the ranking does not mean that the authority's business service has deteriorated, and in many cases it is due to the fact that other authorities ' service to businesses has improved more and they have risen in the rankings, while the authority that declined in the ranking has improved its services to businesses less.
Among the finalists in the rankings are Petah Tikva, which rose from sixth to second place, and Rehovot, which rose from 12th to third place.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from fourth place to 11th place in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to sixth place.
"Business-A Growth Engine"
The ranking indicates that Nof Hagalil leads in local authorities with between 50 and 150 thousand residents.
It is followed by Kiryat Motzkin, Metta Binyamin, Modiin־Maccabim־Reut, Kfar Saba, Raanana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula and Hod Hasharon.
In the 28th and last place is Tiberias.
"The measure is designed to encourage local authorities to make it easier for small and medium-sized businesses, starting from the time the business opens and throughout its activity with the authorities," said Minister of Economy and Industry, Orna Barbayai.
"Businesses are a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and are responsible for about 50% of business output and about 60% of employees in the economy.
The development of small businesses is in the public interest of all of us, but the local authority has a direct impact on the businesses that are in it.
The Corona emphasized the importance of local government, and we saw that authorities who acted and encouraged the promotion of small businesses and found creative solutions for them, became the first governmental interface for them."
Ran Kuiti, Director of the Agency for Small and Medium-Sized Businesses at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: "Local authorities have a central and essential part in the ability of businesses in their fields to thrive and flourish.
In the last two years, as we deal with the coronavirus crisis, the authorities have had a greater role in helping businesses survive in their fields and survive in general."
2021 by mail: 20 parcels per household - and a jump in their weight
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 - similar to 2020 •
The average weight per pack is 435 grams - a 36% jump compared to 2020 •
Busiest month: December, when the average package weight stood at 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million mail packages arrived in Israel, nearly 20 packages on average per household, according to Israel Postal data obtained by Israel Hayom.
The number of packages arriving in 2021 is similar to 2020, when 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and lower than 2019, when 61.6 million packages arrived.
However, this year there has been a more than 36 per cent year־on-year jump in the weight of packages coming from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products came to Israel from abroad, a 36% jump from 14,860 tons in 2020 and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits
The average weight per pack jumped by 60% in two years - from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The increase in the weight of packages is mainly influenced by two major trends, both on the seller's and the buyer's side: the largest overseas shopping sites are uniting items into one shipment and no longer shipping any product from the"shopping basket"in separate packaging.
On the part of the Israeli consumer, the rapid delivery of the shipments, within a few days of the order, supports the purchase of more everyday products such as clothing and gifts, which the purchasers wish to receive near the execution of the purchase.
Also in 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month with the highest number of packages arriving from abroad and the highest number of items was December, with 4.2 million packages weighing a total of 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per pack stood at 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
The Black Friday Effect
More packages arrived in December than in any other month, likely due to November's shopping holidays, such as Chinese Singles Day, Black Friday and Cyber Monday.
The large orders start arriving in Israel between a week and two weeks after purchase.
