State Comptroller's Report: The actual budget for most years of the Pharmaceutical Basket Committee's activity-smaller than the Recommended budget
According to the report by Matanya Engelman – for more than 20 years of Hessel's activity, the Ministry of Health did not supervise the committee's activities •
The report also said that meeting protocols are being published significantly late, if at all •
The comptroller also recommends increasing transparency of the subcommittee's activities – and updating basket work procedures •
Another flaw is that since the committee began its activity, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds for reports on the scope of the uses and utilization of the drugs in the basket – which would have allowed them to analyze and audit the budget given to them.
The Drug Basket Committee is one of the public committees that most influence our daily lives and health.
Every year, the Committee decides on new drugs that will be given to the public free of charge through the health funds – but a new report by the State Comptroller published today (Tuesday) warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without having made control reports on its activity and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Board monitoring and examining its activities.
Israel Hayom correspondent Ran Resnick adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted in the wake of the ongoing revelations in Israel Hayom about drug basket failures.
According to the report by Matanya Engelman, he recommends "making corrections and improvements in the process of expanding the basket, which will result in a higher quality utilization of the basket of health services that the public is entitled to."
Throughout the years of the addition mechanism to the drug basket, in the years 1998-2021, eight billion shekels were added to the state budget – with the addition each year in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add about 800 new medicines and technologies to the health care basket, at a total annual cost of more than two billion shekels.
In practice, the budget allocated to expanding the basket was less than the scope of the requests.
In most years of the commission's operation (90% of the time), the budget supplement was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired supplement rate.
The auditor notes that it is necessary to examine and regulate the height of the annual supplement in order to allow certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that"the model of transparency in basket work is lacking."
Thus, for example, the Basket Committee's working procedure states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 109-160 days, when sometimes the minutes of the final meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in the publication of the protocols undermines the transparency of the decisions; as a result, the ability of the bidders – patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies – to submit repeated requests as soon as possible and relevant, after drawing lessons from the rejection of their proposals, analyzing the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improving and amending their proposals, and re-evaluating the feasibility of accepting them in the next round," he said. The reviewer in the report.
"The Ministry of Health should publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules set out in the procedure."
Out of thousands of submissions, only one financial comment was submitted
Engelman's other criticism concerns the preliminary process of evaluating the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The auditor found that about half (46%) of the submitted technologies did not pass this stage, but the Department of Health does not publish the reasons for the rejection.
Another flaw concerns the activities of the Drug basket subcommittee, which is closed to the media and the public, and where patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The auditor recommends bringing in a public representative or exploring the possibility of making the discussions public without confidential commercial details.
The procedure used by the Health Services Select Committee states that "an economic assessment should be submitted" for a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years only one economic assessment has been submitted out of thousands of submissions – and the commission makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, the Basket Committee hearings for the years 2019-2021 submitted requests to add to the basket of anti-obesity drugs.
The report found that the requests did not include economic estimates, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved by reducing the damage of obesity-related diseases or the ability to avoid gastric bypass surgery.
Further, the decisions of the Drug Basket Committee are inconsistent with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparedness to treat an increase in chronic diseases as goals, but in the framework of the decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The auditor also warns that since 2011, services that are not the responsibility of the HMO are included in the drug basket, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, provided by the Ministry of Health (the"third Supplement").
That is, when the legal framework for this measure is regulated only retrospectively.
In the past six years, NIS 74 million has been used from the addition to the drug basket for these services.
Engelman recommends that the Department of Health update its basket work procedures and also determine whether a separate financial supplement is needed for these services.
About one-third of new drugs that enter the drug basket are defined as"no-cost drugs," whose use does not cost the health funds an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The comptroller proposes to examine the possibility that these drugs will be discussed in a different and abbreviated route, so that the portfolio of drugs can be updated several times a year rather than just once a year.
There is no control over the use of expensive drugs.
The audit also shows that since the Basket Committee began its work 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked the HMO to report and has not monitored the scope of the uses and utilization of the drugs in the basket, information that could have allowed the Ministry to analyze and audit the budget given to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports relating to the years 2006-2009 were published, and these were also published significantly late (the last one was published this year and dealt with the exploitation of the budget in 2007-2009).
"The delay in conducting tests can lead to difficulty in collecting and analyzing the data, to the irrelevance of the conclusions drawn from the examination after such a long period, to the underperformance of the subcommittee and to decisions based on non-final findings," the report said.
The ministry also does not audit and monitor the use of particularly expensive drugs and has not done any research.
These are 10 drugs that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket (NIS 1.7 billion in 2016-2021).
The auditor wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health carry out individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the extent of their use compared to the estimates.
Controls and analysis will enable systemic conclusions to be drawn about the work process of the select committee and the subcommittee, and how the estimates are prepared when pricing drugs and technologies and to improve them."
