Prof. Galia Rahav, Director of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Sheba |
the late Prof. Marvin Shapira
The Meeting that Opened my eyes - and Changed my Life
If I hadn't met the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, who was the director of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Hadassah Hospital, I probably would have remained a specialist in internal medicine.
He was the one who made me love the field of infectious diseases and inspired me to pursue it.
I met him in the corridors of Hadassah, then in the 1980s.
For a moment I did not think that I would leave the inner, for I loved the treatment of the patient himself; but Prof. Shapira showed me that the field of infectious diseases is also expressed in neurology, in the inner as well, and in virtually every area.
I thank him for bringing me into this field.
All along, I've loved his investigative approach, an approach that gets to the bottom of the problem.
Discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor of all intents and purposes, who loved the patients and taught me not to take things for granted and to look into everything.
He was a genuine and honest man, devoid of ego, qualities I loved very much about him.
Initially, when I was asked to choose a doctor who was a role model for me and influenced me the most, I was going to choose my father, the late Dr. Joseph Rakover, a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in a partisan unit.
He was an amazing doctor, who inspired me to go to medicine - but he also reminds me of Marvin Shapiro.
Both, for example, coined proverbs that doctors still use to this day - for example, "Tissue is de ischio," meaning that taking a biopsy of tissue from an infected organ allows you to know which drugs you should give; or "won yo hughes it, yo luz it," which is meant to explain that overuse of antibiotics leads to bacteria becoming resistant to it.
The late Shapira was married to a physiotherapist who worked at Hadassah and the father of two daughters.
He passed away about a year ago, and when I visited his family at seven I cried.
He was something - a witty and clever epidemiologist, who volunteered for everything.
He never complained, not even during his illness.
He was one of the first doctors on the team to treat epidemics, and he is sorely missed during this period.
Had he been with us today, I'm sure I would have consulted him, and I'm sure he would have been one of the leaders of the team to tackle epidemics.
Brought to Light: Meital Yasur Beit-Or
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh, Director of Soroka Hospital |
the Late Prof. Shaul Sukenik
A teacher and friend who supported me and raised generations of doctors
.
I first met the late Prof. Shaul Sukenik when I was a student in the fourth year of my medical studies, and I arrived for a course in internal medicine in Internal Department D, which he managed.
