Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev, Director of the Schneider Children's Center |
About Dr. Tommy Schoenfeld
The man who taught me medicine, and mostly listening.
Dr. Tommy Schoenfeld, founder and former director of the intensive care Unit at Schneider Children's, taught me to be an intensive care doctor, but more than that - he taught me to think.
The obvious thing I learned from him is to care for the most complex, sickest children.
The children, some of whom were healthy just a moment ago, are now between life and death.
The obvious one is to have very difficult conversations, perhaps the most difficult, with families who never imagined they would be caught up in these complex situations in an intensive care unit with their children.
Sounds strange, but it's the obvious one.
But I learned even more profound and profound things from him.
Looking back, because I am a doctor who is a manager and a manager who is a doctor, it is clear to me today that the connection between the worlds is clear; the education I received from Dr. Sheinfeld connects them.
Dr. Sheinfeld taught me to listen attentively to many things: to listen to the children, to listen to the monitor, to listen to the nurse practitioners, to the young and old staff, and to listen to the parents.
All this needs to be done not only to communicate more correctly and successfully, but to constantly gather a great deal of information that can prevent the next deterioration.
The preventative processes in pediatric care exist everywhere, and of course in intensive care.
Listening and talking engenders a deeper understanding, both from the care team and from the patients and their families.
My understanding today as a manager is that these insights are also true in looking at an entire system.
