Medical Malpractice in various stages of birth
In order to win damages,the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that the damage was caused by that negligence
Birth is one of the most joyous and exciting events in a family's life.
However, unfortunately, sometimes births end in severe damage caused to the mother or newborn as a result of the negligence of the medical staff.
In cases where the birth ended in physical injury, the newborn or the mother has room to examine the events that led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in the field of medical malpractice will examine whether there were flaws in the conduct of the medical team during the various stages of birth that caused the damage and, if he sees fit, will consult a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every error in care on the part of the medical staff amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during the birth do not necessarily indicate that her management was negligent.
When, then, is it negligence?
When the doctor's mistake resulted from ineptitude or deviation from the reasonable level of caution, and the ineptitude and deviation from the acceptable level of caution caused harm to the patient that would not have been caused if the doctor had not acted in this way.
In this article, we will examine the different stages of childbirth, explain what complications can occur at each stage and when they arise to be treated.
Stage of contractions
The labor phase lasts an average of 8 to 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix gradually opens (in order to allow the passage of the fetus during childbirth) and at the end of the process should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most cases of medical malpractice in the contraceptive phase involve failure to identify fetal distress prior to birth, which caused damage to the newborn, sometimes even cerebral palsy.
Cerebral Palsy (CP):
Cerebral palsy can be caused by a failure to recognize or delay in identifying a grandparent's breast, which is manifested in a failure to supply oxygen to the brain tissue of the fetus.
As a rule, monitoring the condition of the newborn and correctly decoding the monitor that monitors fetal heart activity should lead to early detection of fetal distress development, allowing the medical team to act quickly and extract the newborn before it is irreversibly damaged.
Cases in which the medical team ignores signs indicating that the fetus is suffering from a lack of oxygen or that the staff misinterprets the data in front of it, especially the fetal monitor, or responds belatedly to the distress expressed by the monitor may constitute negligence.
Cerebral palsy can also be caused by a prolapse of the umbilical cord as well as a rupture of the uterus that was not detected in a timely manner.
Even in these difficult events it is important to ascertain whether the medical staff acted properly.
For example, Adv. Anna Rafe Liganza, of Sror & Co., a financial firm that specializes in representing victims of medical malpractice, said that her firm handled the case of a child who was injured during his birth after the midwife ruptured the amniotic sac when the head of the fetus was too high, resulting in a prolapse of the umbilical cord (when the umbilical cord precedes the head of the fetus) and injury In the supply of oxygen to the fetal brain (as a result of pressure of the fetal head on the umbilical cord) and being born with a severe neurological injury.
In another case, the lawyer said that her office had filed a claim due to gross medical negligence by the maternity ward staff at a large hospital who, during labor, failed to identify in time clear signs that warranted a real suspicion that the woman was suffering from a rupture of the uterus in the surgical scar area of her previous pregnancy.
The fetus, which was ejected through the tear in its mother's womb into the abdominal cavity, suffered from severe fetal distress until it was rescued at a late stage when it was on the verge of death.
Due to the severe fetal suffering during birth, the child had a complex neurological disability.
We will emphasize that in order to win damages, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal connection between the negligence of the medical staff that resulted in the failure to identify the tinnitus and the damage caused to the newborn, i.e. that the damage was caused due to such negligence and not for any other reason or cause.
The examination of the causal relationship will be carried out by examining medical indicators that according to the medical literature only in the existence of which there is a causal relationship between the tinnitus and the brain injury.
Among other things, measures of the pH level in the foetus's blood, its apgar scores, the existence of neurological and systemic injury, and more are examined.
Fetal Death
Stage of Active birth
The stage of active delivery begins when the opening of the cervix reaches a diameter of 10 cm and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical stage.
Delay in birth and avoiding C-section
In some cases, a dysfunctional birth develops, i.e., a lack of progress of the active birth process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a C-section, in order to prevent various damage that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay in birth.
"There are cases where failure to perform a C-section in a timely manner can cause irreparable harm to the fetus," Reif-Liganza explained.
"For example, we handled a medical malpractice claim of a birth death caused by a significant delay in performing a C-section.
Contrary to all recognized medical practice, the medical staff failed to recognize the fetal distress and perform a C-section despite the extremely slow progress of the birth.
The delay in performing the surgery caused systemic damage to the newborn which ultimately led to her death shortly after birth."
Negligence in Vacuum Birth
In situations where the mother or fetus is in significant danger, which requires a particularly rapid termination of the birth, sometimes a vacuum birth is carried out.
In this process, a "dome" vacuum is attached to the head of the fetus and forcibly pulls the fetus out.
Naturally, this action involves dangers and can cause damage to both the fetus and the mother, and therefore requires great care, precision and skill.
In these events, medical negligence may manifest itself in the fact that the doctor does not adhere to the mandatory guidelines and carries out the operation despite the existence of a counter-label, such as when the head of the fetus is too high in the pelvis, or performs it for longer than permitted, or when despite the failure of many attempts, the doctor continues and repeats the action more than the permitted number of attempts.
In these cases, if the negligent action of the vacuum caused damage to the newborn – among other things, it may cause cranial damage and bleeds that may cause brain damage – there is room for a tort claim to be filed.
ERB Paralysis
Erb paralysis is a congenital nerve injury in the brachial plexus (a nerve node that connects the spine to the upper part of the shoulder) and when it occurs during childbirth it is worth examining whether the damage occurred as a result of the negligence of the obstetric staff.
The injury is caused by weakness of the arm muscles and can result in complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in removing the newborn due to the occurrence of a 'shoulder injury' - an obstetric emergency that occurs when the foetus's shoulders become trapped inside the birth canal after its head has come out.
When should you suspect that the paralysis is caused by medical malpractice?
In cases where an assessment of the weight of the fetus indicated that it was a macrosomial fetus, that is, it is expected to be born weighing in excess of 4.5 kg and according to the guidelines it is better to deliver the mother by caesarean section.
When the weight of the newborn is over 4 kg, a C-section should be considered in light of the risk factors including gestational diabetes and the lengthening of the second stage of birth.
In the event that the medical team ignores the assessment of abnormal weight of the fetus or other risk factors and chooses to proceed with vaginal delivery and the risk of ERB shoulder injury and paralysis is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical negligence.
Indeed, in CA 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that"the risk of shoulder stenosis occurring during childbirth can be foreseen with some degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where it is feared to occur, is to conduct a caesarean section."
Placenta Exit Stage
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to the contraction of the uterus after the newborn's exit and is accompanied by bleeding.
In most cases, the procedure lasts up to half an hour from the moment the baby is born and often occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical team.
After the placenta is removed, the medical team will check whether it has come out intact or whether parts of the placenta remain in the uterus.
During this stage, complications may occur that may cause severe damage to the mother.
One of the known complications resulting from placenta residue in the uterus is called Ascherman syndrome, scarring of the uterine wall resulting from inflammation caused by placenta residue in the uterus, a phenomenon that damages the endometrial in a way that makes it impossible to instill pregnancy.
Therefore, in cases where the medical team did not recognize that placenta residue remained or did not take all measures to prevent endometrial damage despite the suspicion of placenta residue in the womb, it is possible that this is medical negligence and the case deserves a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer in the field.
Birth Death
The death of a newborn during childbirth is fairly rare.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy to the whole family sadly becomes the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the newborn in a timely manner or respond belatedly to such bleeding.
"For example..."In that case, the medical team ignored and failed to respond to the mother's alarming vital signs, for long hours, and was late in diagnosing massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the background disease from which she suffered, "Reif-Liganza said.
"In another case..."Our firm represented the relatives of a woman who died after the birth of twins due to bleeding that originated from the caesarean section that was not properly sewn.
In that case, the mother complained of severe pain and weakness after the surgery, but the medical team did not properly address her complaints and her clinical condition, she responded late only after her systems began to fail, leading to her death."
Uterine loss
In severe cases, medical malpractice in childbirth can lead to a hysterectomy, says Attorney Rafe Lingza:"Our firm has conducted a lawsuit against a hospital that is based on hysterectomy due to medical malpractice after birth.
In the same case, the mother, a 31-year-old woman, lost her uterus due to a lack of proper care for the massive bleeding observed by the medical team after birth and yet no action was taken in time that could have prevented the damage."
What are the damages awarded in medical malpractice lawsuits at birth?
Neonatal compensation for injury due to medical malpractice at birth includes many components of damage, with the most significant amounts given for pain and suffering, nursing and paid care, loss of wages and pensions to the injured person and even his parents, and other components of damage.
The compensation paid to an injured minor for wage and pension losses is calculated in most cases on the basis of the average salary in the economy.
In addition, the compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitative accessories, the cost of adjusting housing for the needs of the baby, mobility and more.
"The amount of compensation is determined on a case-by-case basis and according to its circumstances,"says Attorney Reif-Liganza,adding that "today most of the claims on the grounds of medical malpractice are settled in a compromise that takes into account the chance and risk each party has in conducting the procedure." Then if the claim is not rejected, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages and, for example, as part of a lawsuit managed by our firm, the District Court awarded a minor who suffered cerebral palsy due to a delay in identifying fetal distress a compensation in excess of 10 million shekels."
In summary
Medical malpractice at birth is undoubtedly every family's nightmare.
In these cases, a proper legal examination of the events that caused the tragic outcome, by an attorney skilled at handling claims on the grounds of medical malpractice, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
