Study states: Zoom meetings hurt creativity
Some 2,100 engineers and academics around the world have been asked to develop solutions to the problem-some in video sessions, some in face-to-face meetings •
Result: Virtual meeting impairs creativity and thinking outside the box •
Study leader at Columbia University: "The visual focus on the screen impairs the idea-making process" •
There is no harm to productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the impact of video-software encounters on the creativity of participants, compared to face-to-face encounters.
Unfortunately, creativity has been found to be impaired in virtual meetings through screens.
The question of the study - led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University - was whether remote computer meetings preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of the distance.
The study itself began as early as 2016 but received a big boost in the two years, during which many workers moved to work from home.
"People in a personal meeting move around the room, use objects and use them for creative thinking," Brooks says.
"In a computer session, however, the concentration in maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more focused on video when interacting, which impairs the broad and expansive idea-making process."
Space is narrowing.
To test the results and see if they would be repeated, they were tested twice – once at Columbia University and again in real life - on engineers who knew each other from early acquaintance.
At the university, the researchers divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two parts: in one, the subjects were asked to meet in person and develop solutions to the problem, and in the other, they were asked to do so through a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to share similarly and solve in a new way a problem presented to them.
In both cases, there was a decline in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking among those who had met on video.
Jay Olson, a postdoc at McGill University in Canada and a researcher on ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his view, as part of a thinking activity, people often look at their surroundings to help create ideas, whereas in a video session the thinking converges to the screen rather than expanding in a way that allows creativity.
"When people are in the same room, they look around them and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can give them new associations.
On the other hand, research shows that relationships through a computer change our attention so that we are more focused on the inside and the screen, and this reduces innovation and idea creation through looking at the environment and thinking outwards."
There is no impediment to critical thinking.
However, before managers run employees back to the offices, the researchers note that "working through a computer did not damage productivity itself nor people's critical thinking on innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
That is, the harm is focused on creativity only and not on the other forms of work in front of a computer."
Ellen Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also disputed the findings.
She said:"There is a difference between just creativity, like new uses for frisbee (one of the research questions; AG), and solutions of work.
It may also be that when employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or work from home, creativity will improve."
Both Prof Langer and Dr Olson also suggested future research in which such meetings would be stopped for states of mind and wandering around the room to see how this activity would affect the end result.
Dr. Olson also suggested that following the study only for brainstorming sessions, employees would return to work, and as a rule he suggested not to be alarmed by one study but to do more research in the field.
"I wouldn't want workers to be forcibly returned and not be happy is a bigger hit," he says.
