We looked at: What do the side effects after the coronavirus vaccine mean?
Many people who get vaccinated feel weakness, fever and fatigue after getting the shot, while others feel nothing •
Could this indicate a stronger immune system of those who do experience these symptoms, or is this a unfounded rumor?
As more and more people get vaccinated, the lack of information about side effects continues to confuse and create rumors, most of which are untrue.
Is the immune system of those who have developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies have responded less harshly to the vaccine, which might prove that their system is unable to fight off a foreign body that has entered the body?
"There are several levels of responses to the vaccine,"says Dr. David Dvir, head of the United Primary Medicine Department and a member of the advisory committee for the CTM (Pandemic Treatment Team), reassuring:"Headaches, fatigue, pain in the place, these are the immediate reactions of the immune system.
This is how the body responds to the entry of a foreign body into the system."
Is there a link between the levels of antibodies that develop and the side effects?
"There is no correlation between the sensations and the development of antibodies against the virus.
About 50-60% feel the side effects, but about 90% develop protection against the virus.
People who developed strong reactions were not found to be more protected."
"In the medical literature, there is no correlation between immediate response and vaccination levels.
In some of the trials in which people were also given placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
It's also a mental component-how the person perceives the vaccine, if they expect there to be side effects.
A lot of the phenomena that happen could also happen normally, but because the public has been vaccinated it attributes the response to the vaccine itself, and this is a bias that you see about vaccines in general - attribution of phenomena that happen next to the vaccine and are attributed to it."
According to Dr. Dvir, the causes of the common reported symptoms, such as weakness and headaches, are not yet known.
Regarding myocarditis, opinions differ.
"There are all sorts of theories about this, but it should be noted that the virus itself causes higher rates of myocarditis than the vaccine.
One theory is that it's a strong immune response."
Is it even possible to assess the strength of an immune system?
"When students were exposed to the flu virus, it was shown that those who did not sleep or who were more stressed were more vulnerable to infection.
Besides, there are laboratory parameters that test the immune system or its ingredients.
When there's a decline in the immune system, you see it right away.
People get a lot of viral or infectious diseases.
It's not like someone is walking around with a weak immune system and not aware of it.
These are people who come to inquiries because of recurrent events of infectious diseases, and what affects the system are banal things: stress, diet, sleep.
By the way, we also don't want too strong an immune system, because it can cause autoimmune diseases."
Soon, MRNA vaccines will appear in more contexts, thanks to the vast knowledge that has accumulated about them in recent times.
"There is no doubt that this will open the door to other vaccines of this kind.
This technology is being tested for many uses beyond vaccines - for treating oncology diseases, for example.
Their effectiveness is that the material stays very little time in the body-going in, doing its act, and then falling apart.
This technology is not new, but it has received a major boost due to the great need for a rapid vaccine.
Now, for example, we know that the three-week interval between dose and dose is too small, and some vaccine experts say that after a third dose we may not need another vaccine in the near term, so it's not clear whether we're going to get vaccinated every six months or if the third dose will give a bigger spread."
Thousands hurt: Severe privacy outage on Route 6
Route 6 customers?
Your personal information, including full name, addresses, payment amounts and full details of your trips, may have been compromised •
According to the Privacy Protection Authority, the Derech Eretz company violated the Privacy Protection Law and its regulations.
After a report by Derech Eretz, the operator of Route 6 in Israel, about a security incident that occurred at the company, the Privacy Protection Authority began an enforcement procedure.
As part of the incident, security weaknesses were discovered on its payments website, which allowed a lot of information from the accounts of the member's customers to be exposed for all to see.
Among other things, customers ' payment invoices were exposed over a short period of time and these invoices included personal information, including first and last name, payment amounts, vehicle location, travel dates and what hours.
In addition, because the company did not record as required by law the access to its systems, it is not possible to know accurately during what period unauthorized parties were able to access the company's systems.
In the breach letter, which the Privacy Protection Authority forwarded to the company, the Authority emphasized that most large companies and organizations in the economy are required to adopt a dynamic information security policy, and that as threats and risks develop, the organization must carefully examine the updated risks and act in accordance with the customary security measures in the circumstances, in accordance with the nature of the database and its nature.
As a result, companies and organizations have a duty to update their systems and conduct risk surveys and penetration tests, in order to assess and prepare for the changing risks.
In addition, companies and organizations are required to use an automatic documentation mechanism and to conduct training for employees, in accordance with the provisions of the Privacy Protection (Information Security) Regulations.
According to the inspection findings, the Authority determined that the company violated the provisions of the Privacy Protection Law and its regulations, and required the Company to take a number of corrective actions.
Road Haaretz, operator of Route 6, said: "The issue has been dealt with in accordance with the strictest requirements."
