Exempted from isolation for the vaccinated and recovering from non-red states, the foreign tourists are returning.
Those arriving in Israel received notices from the Ministry of Health that they were exempt from the quarantine duty upon receiving a negative response to the coronavirus test •
It was only later that the ministry issued an official statement saying only that it was only passengers from orange countries, although those returning from red countries also reported receiving the message. •
In addition, tourists from orange destinations will be able to enter the country and many red destinations are expected to be removed from the list.
At the height of the epidemic - the end to isolation for returnees from abroad?
The Ministry of Health sent notices to those returning to Israel this morning, according to which they are exempt from isolation upon receiving a negative response to the coronavirus test they performed after landing in Israel.
It's also about returning from red states.
Some of the messages sent informed returnees that they could be released after receiving a negative answer or after 24 hours at the latest, and some received the exemption after receiving the negative answer.
Only after that was an official announcement from the Ministry of Health stating that starting at midnight, 4.1.2022, vaccinated or recovering persons returning from Orange countries will undergo a PCR test at Ben Gurion Airport and will be quarantined for 24 hours or until they receive a negative result (the earliest).
The decision will be enshrined in the executive order of the Ministry of Health and will be submitted for approval by the Knesset Health Committee.
The ministry clarified that vaccinated or recovering persons who have already returned to Israel from an Orange country and received a negative result from the PCR test they performed at the entrance to Israel, will end the isolation at midnight tonight and are not obligated to perform a second test.
However, travelers from red states reported getting the message, too.
Those who have not been vaccinated or recovered and returned from an Orange state will be placed in home isolation for 14 days, with the possibility of shortened isolation upon receiving a negative result in a PCR test performed from the 7th day of landing in Israel (landing day is the first day).
The decision to lift most of the restrictions on travelers and especially those who are vaccinated comes a day before a High Court hearing brought by the Association of Travel Agencies, Open Skies Headquarters and the Hotel Association.
In a hearing to be held tomorrow, the petitioners are expected to demand that all other red states be removed from the list, with Professor Itamar Grotto backing them in his opinion.
Strangers can also enter.
The Prime Minister and the ministers of foreign Affairs, health, Interior, tourism and transport agreed that starting on Sunday 9.1.2022, vaccinated/recovering foreigners (according to the Ministry of Health definition) from Orange countries will be allowed entry - this is subject to filling out an online form in advance, carrying out a PCR or antigen test before boarding the plane, conducting a PCR test at the entrance to Israel and then entering isolation for 24 hours Hours or getting a negative answer on the test (the earliest).
Non-vaccinated/ non-recovering foreigners (as defined by the Ministry of Health) will not be allowed to enter Israel.
Foreigners from red states, except those whose entry has been approved by the Exceptions Committee, will not be allowed to enter Israel.
The team outline will not be renewed at this time.
What about red states?
The Committee on the Classification of Countries in the Ministry of Health recommends to the government the Committee recommends removing from the red list of countries and moving to the orange list the countries: South Africa, Hungary, Nigeria, Spain, Portugal, France, Canada.
The countries that currently remain on the red list are the United Arab Emirates, the United States, Ethiopia, the United Kingdom, Tanzania, Mexico, Switzerland and Turkey.
Another option being explored by the Department of Health is to exempt vaccinated people returning from red states.
At the moment, it is unclear whether there is a connection between the messages received this morning by those returning to Israel and the guidelines that may be received by the Ministry of Health on this issue.
The Department of Health has yet to receive a response.
The sky is starting to open up: Health Ministry changes restrictions on gates
Vaccinators returning from orange states will be subject to 24-hour isolation •
The US, Turkey, UK and UAE countries will be red-flagged.
After long weeks in which it was very difficult to find a destination to which to fly without restrictions, and after all returnees from abroad were charged with isolation, along with a ban on the entry of tourists to Israel - yesterday it was decided to change the procedures and significantly ease the restrictions on Ben Gurion Airport.
The Ministry of Health decided to recommend eliminating the three-day quarantine requirement for Israelis returning from orange countries.
So far, anyone vaccinated - or recovering under the Health Ministry's definition who has returned from an Orange state-has been quarantined for three days, subject to two coronavirus tests.
Currently, the isolation that the vaccinated and recovering persons returning from orange countries will have to enter is for a maximum of 24 hours, or until the results of the coronavirus tests performed after landing at Ben Gurion Airport (the earliest) are received.
Those who are not vaccinated or recovering will nevertheless be required to enter seven days of isolation subject to two coronavirus tests, or 14 days without the second test, whether they have returned from an orange or red country.
A vaccinated or recovering person returning from a red state must also be in full isolation.
The latest list of red countries recommended by the Health Ministry, which still needs to be approved by the government, includes the US, Turkey, Tanzania, Ethiopia, Mexico, the UK, Switzerland and the UAE.
In all countries, except Turkey, the average number of people entering the country in the past two weeks is more than 5% of the total, automatically putting them on the Red list.
The rate of increase among patients from Turkey is rapid, the rate of positive returns from it stands at just over 4%, so it was decided to put it on the red List as well.
The most prominent countries to be removed from the red list are France, Spain, Portugal and Canada.
Thus, from January 9, tourists who are vaccinated according to the requirements of the Ministry of Health will be able to enter Israel without the need for isolation, similar to the conditions of Israelis returning from an Orange state.
In this case, too, the decision is subject to approval by the government, which will discuss the matter in the coming days.
It is important to note that there are few cases in which the government does not approve the recommendations of the Ministry of Health in this area.
Tourists are against the restrictions.
The Association of Travel Agencies, Open Skies Headquarters and the Hotel Association have filed a petition with the High Court to lift the travel restrictions.
The state lifted most of the restrictions yesterday, but left eight significant states on the red List.
In a hearing to be held this morning in Jerusalem, the petitioners are expected to demand that the state cancel the list of red states.
One person who will support the petitioners ' position is Prof. Itamar Grotto, who is expected to attend the hearing.
Tourism Minister Yoel Razvazov, who in recent weeks has supported easing restrictions on the entry of foreign tourists to Israel, said yesterday: "The cancellation of the quarantine for those who return from abroad and the return of tourism to those who are vaccinated are the right and right thing at this time.
I thank my colleagues in government, who understood the plight of the tourism industry and agreed with me that the harm outweighed the benefit.
The vaccine is the best response to the epidemic, and as such, the vaccinated public deserves to conduct a life - enabling routine alongside the coronavirus."
